  "What is the 'recursive nature' of cofactor expansion?": "",
  "The matrix must be expanded along every row": "",
  "The expansion must be repeated until all entries are positive": "",
  "The same formula is applied to progressively smaller matrices until reaching a base case": "",
  "The determinant is computed by recursion on the matrix size, but only for symmetric matrices": "",
  "Cofactor expansion reduces an nxn determinant to a sum of (n-1)x(n-1) determinants. Each of these can be expanded further, recursing down to 2x2 or 1x1 base cases.": "",
  "What does 'expanding along a row' mean?": "",
  "Computing det(A) = sum of a_{ij} * C_{ij} for j = 1 to n, where i is the chosen row": "",
  "Multiplying all entries in the row by the row number": "",
  "Inserting a new row into the matrix": "",
  "Adding entries of the row together": "",
  "Expanding along row i means fixing the row index i and summing over all columns j: det(A) = a_{i1}C_{i1} + a_{i2}C_{i2} + ... + a_{in}C_{in}.": "",
  "What is the 'adjugate' (classical adjoint) matrix?": "",
  "The row-reduced form of the matrix": "",
  "The transpose of the matrix of cofactors": "",
  "The conjugate of the matrix": "",
  "The matrix of minors": "",
  "The adjugate adj(A) is the transpose of the cofactor matrix. It satisfies A * adj(A) = det(A) * I, which gives the formula A^(-1) = adj(A)/det(A).": "",
